Think of JWT as a digital passport: it contains claims (user info) signed by the server so the API knows who you are without sending your password each time. The backend verifies the signature, checks the expiry, and extracts the token’s payload.

```rust
fn validate_jwt(token: &str) -> Result<serde_json::Value, Box<dyn Error>> {
    let header = base64::{engine::UrlSafeEncoder}::decode(&token[..len(token)-1])?;
    let payload = base64::{engine::UrlSafeEncoder}::decode(header)?;
    Ok(serde_json::from_str(payload).map_err(|e| Box::new(e)))
}
